In physical terms, spontaneity is subject to Gibb’s definition, where ΔG (change in free energy) corresponds to ΔH (change in enthalpy) and ΔS (change in entropy), according to the following equation:ΔG=ΔH−TΔS\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$ \Delta G=\Delta H-T\Delta S $$\end{document}

For specific processes, the change in free energy may be determined without referring to the presented mechanism and instead relying on reaction dynamics; specifically, on the ratio of product and substrate concentrations:ΔG=ΔG0+RT∗lnC∗D/A∗B\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$ \Delta G=\Delta {G}^0+{RT}^{\ast}\mathit{\ln}\left\{\left(\left[C\right]\ast \left[D\right]\right)/\left(\left[A\right]\ast \left[B\right]\right)\right\} $$\end{document}R, gas constant; T, absolute temperature.

If the process is in equilibrium, ΔG becomes equal to 0, and thus, according to the formula, ΔG0 is given asΔG0=−RTlnK\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
